CLAUDE.md — Leadership Companion for Cursor> **This file is automatically read by Claude Code on every session start.**> **It contains the full architecture context for the Leadership Companion product.**What This Project IsAn AI-powered decision support companion for business leaders, sold self-serve at $29/month (Starter) and $59/month (Pro). Founding Pro: $49/month for the first year. Primary vertical: construction (452,820 businesses in Australia, 5,000+ collapses since 2022). Built on a behavioural science instruction layer + technical architecture.The user opens the app and talks or types. No dashboards, no settings pages. The AI responds with domain-specific insight, follow-up questions, and practical frameworks. What makes it different from ChatGPT: 4-layer memory that builds understanding over time, 24 knowledge bricks with deep domain overlays, an agent layer that follows up between sessions, and a decision journal that tracks patterns.Mission: Ship Day 7. Charge Day 8. Cash positive Month 1. 500 users Month 4–6.Domain: leadershipcompanion.co---Tech StackRuntime: Node.js + TypeScriptFramework: Express (API routes, SSE streaming)Database: PostgreSQL (RDS, AES-256 encryption, forced TLS) + pgvector extension (Layer 4 semantic search)Auth: Clerk (authentication, JWT issuance)Payments: Stripe ($29 Starter, $59 Pro, $49 Founding Pro)LLM Primary: Anthropic Claude Sonnet (conversation, profile updates)LLM Secondary: Anthropic Claude Haiku (summaries, decision extraction)Voice: Deepgram STT (speech-to-text)Email: Amazon SES (nudges, transactional emails)Scheduling: Amazon EventBridge + Lambda (agent cron jobs)Hosting: AWS App Runner (single container at launch)File Storage: Amazon S3 (encrypted, user attachments + quarterly review artefacts)Cache (Month 2+): Redis via ElastiCacheFrontend: Single-page app, minimal UI — conversation window is the product---Architecture: Modular MonolithAll 9 modules live in a single App Runner container and a single codebase. Each module is in its own directory, exports a clean API matching the contracts below, and has zero knowledge of other modules' internals.The #1 RuleNo module reads or writes another module's tables directly. If M7 needs profile data, it calls `M5.memory.getAgentContext()`, not `SELECT * FROM user_profiles`. Break this and you can never extract modules to services later.Directory Structure```/src  /modules    /auth          → M1: Auth & Billing    /engine        → M2: Conversation Engine    /assembler     → M3: Context Assembler    /bricks        → M4: Brick Engine    /memory        → M5: Memory Manager    /decisions     → M6: Decision Tracker    /agent         → M7: Agent Scheduler    /events        → M8: Event Logger    /voice         → M9: Voice Processor  /shared    /contracts     → TypeScript interfaces for ALL internal APIs (source of truth)    /middleware     → Auth middleware, rate limiting, error handling    /db            → Database connection, migrations  /api    /routes        → External API routes (thin layer calling M1/M3)```Each module directory contains: `index.ts` (exports the public API matching contracts), internal files (implementation), and tests (unit tests against the contract). No module imports from another module's internal files — only from its index.ts exports.Extraction TestCan you take any module's directory, move it to a separate service, replace internal function calls with HTTPS calls using the same contract, and have it work? If yes, boundaries are clean.---The 9 ModulesDependency Flow```Frontend  |  v[M1 Auth] -----> [M3 Context Assembler] -----> [M8 Event Logger]  |                |         |         |  v                v         v         v                 [M2]      [M4]      [M5]      [M6]                  |                              |                  v                              v               LLM APIs                [M7 Agent Scheduler]                                         |                                         v                                  [M2] + [M5] + SES[M9 Voice] → text → [M3]   (voice is just a text source)```Module DetailsID	Module	Owns	Dependencies	Build PhaseM8	Event Logger	session_events table. Fire-and-forget sink. All analytics.	None	Day 1M1	Auth & Billing	Clerk + Stripe. User lifecycle, JWT, cancellation + churn reason + pause. Two-tier billing ($29 Starter, $59 Pro, $49 Founding Pro). Upgrade/downgrade flows. Founding member flag.	None	Day 1M2	Conversation Engine	Stateless LLM wrapper. Prompt in, streamed response + parsed metadata out.	None	Day 1–2M4	Brick Engine	brick_knowledge table. Brick lookup. Mode 2 state. Deep overlay loading.	None	Day 2–3M5	Memory Manager	Layers 1–4. Sessions, summaries, profiles, semantic retrieval.	M2 (background)	Day 2–5M3	Context Assembler	Orchestrator. Calls M2+M4+M5. Assembles prompt. Mode 2 detection. On session end: fetches brick summariser instructions from M4, passes to M5 for background summarisation.	M2, M4, M5, M8	Day 3–4M6	Decision Tracker	Background extraction. Decision journal. Follow-up tracking.	M2 (Haiku)	Week 2M7	Agent Scheduler	Lambda cron. Nudge generation + delivery (SES + Twilio/SNS for SMS). Tracking. Tier-aware: full follow-ups for Pro, taste nudges for Starter after week 3. Delivery channel routing (email/SMS/both per user preference).	M2, M5	Day 5+M9	Voice Processor	Deepgram STT. Audio in, text out. M3 doesn't know/care.	None	Week 2Key Module RulesM2 (Conversation Engine) is stateless. It receives a fully assembled prompt and returns a response. No knowledge of users, sessions, bricks, or memory.M3 (Context Assembler) is the only orchestrator. It's the only module that calls multiple other modules.M8 (Event Logger) is fire-and-forget. Every module pushes events to M8 asynchronously. M8 never blocks.Background jobs are async. When M3 needs a session summary (M5) or decision capture (M6), it pushes async. The user never waits for background work.---Internal API ContractsThese are the exact interfaces between modules. In the monolith, these are TypeScript function calls. When extracted to services, they become HTTPS endpoints with the same shapes.Rule: if you change a contract's shape, update the interface file in /src/shared/contracts/ first, then fix all callers.M3 → M2: conversation.stream```typescriptinterface ConversationStreamInput {  systemPrompt: string;  messages: Message[];  model: 'sonnet' | 'haiku';  streamCallback: (token: string) => void;}interface ConversationStreamOutput {  fullResponse: string;  metadata: {    bricks: number[];    confidence: 'high' | 'medium' | 'low';    topic_shift: boolean;    decision: boolean;    emotional_tone: 'stressed' | 'frustrated' | 'low_energy' | 'positive' | 'neutral';    brick_signals: Record<number, string> | null;  // Brick-specific longitudinal signals, e.g. {24:'imposter_pattern'}  };  inputTokens: number;  outputTokens: number;  ttftMs: number;  costUsd: number;}```Streaming: tokens delivered via callback as they arrive. Metadata parsed from `<meta>` tags after full response. Response returned to caller has metadata stripped. Cost calculated from token counts. `brick_signals` is a sparse map populated only when a loaded deep overlay detects something worth tracking longitudinally.M3 → M4: bricks.getContext```typescriptinterface BricksGetContextInput {  brickIds: number[];  sessionId: string;  includeDeepOverlay: boolean;  industry: string | null;}interface BricksGetContextOutput {  contexts: Array<{    brickId: number;    shortDescription: string;    deepOverlay: string | null;    constructionOverlay: string | null;  }>;  totalTokens: number;  newBricks: number[];  // Bricks not yet loaded this session — triggers Mode 2}```If `includeDeepOverlay=true`, returns deep overlay for bricks not yet loaded in this session. If `industry='construction'`, appends construction overlay.M3 → M4: bricks.getMode2FollowUp```typescriptinterface Mode2FollowUpInput {  brickId: number;  previousResponse: string;  industry: string | null;}interface Mode2FollowUpOutput {  transitionPhrase: string;   // Randomly selected from pillar-appropriate options  followUpPrompt: string;     // Pre-formatted prompt for M2  deepOverlay: string;        // Deep overlay to inject}```M3 → M4: bricks.getSummariserInstructions```typescriptinterface GetSummariserInstructionsInput {  brickIds: number[];}interface GetSummariserInstructionsOutput {  instructions: Record<number, string>;  // brickId → summariser instruction text (~50-100 tokens each)  growthSignalDefs: Record<number, string[]>;  // brickId → list of growth signal keys to extract}```Called by M3 when triggering background summarisation. Returns brick-specific instructions that tell Haiku what to look for and extract from the session transcript. Also returns the growth signal keys so the summariser knows what flags to evaluate.```### M3 → M5: memory.getSessionContext```typescriptinterface GetSessionContextInput {  userId: string;  maxTokens: number;  currentTranscriptTokens: number;}interface GetSessionContextOutput {  profile: { text: string; tokens: number };  summaries: Array<{ text: string; tokens: number; sessionDate: string }>;  recentSessions: Array<{ messages: Message[]; tokens: number }>;  reentryPrompt: string | null;  // 'Last time we discussed X...' for session starts  totalTokens: number;}```If `currentTranscriptTokens > 8000`, returns compressed transcript. `totalTokens` allows M3 to balance against brick context budget.M3 → M5: memory.saveMessage```typescriptinterface SaveMessageInput {  sessionId: string;  userId: string;  role: 'user' | 'assistant';  content: string;  metadata: object | null;}interface SaveMessageOutput {  saved: boolean;  sessionTokenCount: number;  needsSummarisation: boolean;  // true = M3 should request compression next cycle}```M3 → M5: memory.summariseSession (ASYNC/BACKGROUND)```typescriptinterface SummariseSessionInput {  sessionId: string;  userId: string;  activeBrickSummariserInstructions: Record<number, string> | null;  // From M4, brick-specific extraction guidance  activeBrickGrowthSignalDefs: Record<number, string[]> | null;      // From M4, growth signal keys to evaluate}interface SummariseSessionOutput {  summaryText: string;  summaryJson: {    topicsDiscussed: string[];    bricksActivated: number[];    decisionsReferenced: string[];    emotionalArc: string;                                        // e.g. 'stressed > resolved' or 'low throughout'    brickGrowthSignals: Record<number, Record<string, boolean>>; // e.g. {24: {evidence_held: false, instinct_trusted: true}}    brickObservations: Record<number, string> | null;            // Free-text observations per brick, e.g. {24: 'User minimised two achievements, sought reassurance on hiring decision already made'}  };  embeddingStored: boolean;}```Called after session ends. Generates summary via Haiku (calls M2 internally). When `activeBrickSummariserInstructions` is provided, Haiku appends those instructions to its summarisation prompt so it knows what brick-specific signals to extract. Stores summary + vector embedding. Updates user profile via Sonnet, including brick_patterns in profile_json. Fire-and-forget from M3's perspective.M3 → M5: memory.semanticSearch (Week 3)```typescriptinterface SemanticSearchInput {  userId: string;  query: string;  maxResults: number;  maxTokens: number;}interface SemanticSearchOutput {  results: Array<{    summaryText: string;    sessionDate: string;    similarity: number;  }>;  totalTokens: number;}```M3 → M6: decisions.capture (ASYNC/BACKGROUND, Week 2)```typescriptinterface DecisionCaptureInput {  sessionId: string;  userId: string;  transcript: string;}interface DecisionCaptureOutput {  captured: boolean;  decision: {    text: string;    options: string[];    choice: string;    confidence: number;    reasoning: string;    followUpDate: string;  } | null;}```Triggered when `metadata.decision = true`. Sends transcript to Haiku for extraction.M7 → M5: memory.getAgentContext```typescriptinterface GetAgentContextInput {  userId: string;}interface GetAgentContextOutput {  profile: object;  lastSessionSummary: string;  lastSessionDate: string;  activeGoals: string[];  openDecisions: object[];}```Lightweight context fetch for nudge generation. Agent calls this daily for each user in scope.M7 → M2: conversation.generate (non-streaming)```typescriptinterface ConversationGenerateInput {  systemPrompt: string;  messages: Message[];  model: 'haiku' | 'sonnet';  maxTokens: number;}interface ConversationGenerateOutput {  response: string;  tokens: number;  costUsd: number;}```Non-streaming variant. Used by agent scheduler for nudge content and by M5 for background summary/profile generation.* → M8: events.log (fire-and-forget)```typescriptinterface EventLogInput {  eventType: string;  // 'message_processed', 'mode2_triggered', 'brick_activated', 'decision_captured', 'nudge_sent', 'nudge_opened', 'session_started', 'session_ended', 'error'  userId: string;  sessionId: string | null;  data: object;  timestamp: string;}interface EventLogOutput {  logged: boolean;}```M1 → M8: events.log (billing)```typescriptinterface BillingEventInput {  eventType: 'subscription_created' | 'subscription_cancelled' | 'payment_failed';  userId: string;  data: {    plan: string;    cancelReason: string | null;  };}```Frontend → M3: POST /api/conversation/message```typescript// Requestinterface ConversationRequest {  sessionId: string | null;  // null = new session  message: string;  inputType: 'text' | 'voice';  attachments?: Attachment[];  // File uploads (Week 2 feature)}interface Attachment {  filename: string;  mimeType: string;          // 'application/pdf', 'image/jpeg', 'text/csv', etc.  data: string;              // base64 encoded file content  sizeBytes: number;}// Response: Server-Sent Events (SSE) streaminterface SSEEvent {  type: 'token' | 'mode2_transition' | 'mode2_token' | 'done' | 'reentry' | 'error';  content: string;  sessionId?: string;  // returned on 'done'}```The frontend renders 'token' and 'mode2_token' identically — just streaming text. 'mode2_transition' can show a brief thinking indicator. 'reentry' appears only at session start if user has prior sessions.Why SSE, not WebSockets: SSE is simpler, works over HTTP/2 (always TLS-encrypted), no persistent connection manager needed. Sufficient for server→client streaming. Client sends via POST, server streams via SSE. All communication over HTTPS.M3: File Processing Pipeline (internal, Week 2)When `attachments` are present on the conversation request, M3 processes them before assembling the prompt:```typescriptinterface ProcessedAttachment {  attachmentId: string;  filename: string;  mimeType: string;  extractedText: string | null;     // Text extracted from PDFs, XLSX, CSV, DOCX  imageContent: string | null;      // Base64 for images — passed to Sonnet vision  tokenCount: number;  s3Key: string;                    // Encrypted S3 storage reference  summarised: boolean;              // true if Haiku pre-summarised (large files)}```File processing rules:PDFs → extract text via `pdf-parse`. If >4,000 tokens, summarise via Haiku before injectingImages (JPEG, PNG, WEBP) → pass directly to Sonnet as image content blocks (vision). No text extraction neededExcel/CSV → parse to structured text via `xlsx` / `papaparse`. Cap at 4,000 tokensWord docs → extract text via `mammoth`. If >4,000 tokens, summarise via HaikuPlain text → inject directlyMax file size: 10MB per file, 3 files per message at launchSupported types: PDF, JPEG, PNG, WEBP, CSV, XLSX, XLS, DOCX, TXTStorage: All uploaded files stored in encrypted S3 bucket with user-scoped prefix. Lifecycle: deleted 90 days after account deletionToken budget for attachments: 2,000–4,000 tokens. When attachments present, M3 trims session summaries and transcript to stay within overall budget ceiling---Conversation ArchitectureOption B: Single-Call ClassificationEvery user message goes to a single Sonnet call. The system prompt contains short descriptions of all 24 bricks (~50–100 words each, ~1,300 tokens). Sonnet identifies relevant bricks and weights its response. No separate classifier. No extra latency.Hidden MetadataSystem prompt instructs Sonnet to append metadata in `<meta>` tags on every response. Backend parses and strips before display. User never sees it.```<meta>bricks:[1,3,9]|confidence:high|topic_shift:true|decision:false|emotional_tone:stressed|brick_signals:{}</meta>````brick_signals` is a sparse map. Only populated when a loaded deep overlay detects a trackable longitudinal signal. Example with Brick 24 active: `brick_signals:{24:imposter_pattern}`. When no deep overlay is loaded or no signals detected, emit empty: `brick_signals:{}`.No Em-dashesNo Em-Dashes in any outputMode 2: Deep Overlay Follow-UpWhen `topic_shift = true` AND a new brick is detected (not already loaded in session):User gets immediate streaming response from Sonnet (~1.5s to first token)Backend detects new brick, loads deep overlay from brick_knowledge tableBackend sends follow-up prompt to Sonnet with natural transition + deep overlayFollow-up streams to user. Total gap: 2–3 secondsDeep overlay stored in session context. Won't re-trigger for this brickRule: Mode 2 triggers max once per topic thread per session. Max 2 deep overlays active. If a 3rd fires, drop least-recently-used.---Memory ArchitectureAPI has zero memory between calls. Backend assembles context before every call. That assembled context IS the model's entire reality.Layer 1 — Hot: Full transcript of last 2–3 sessions. Loaded every call. Build Day 1–2.Layer 2 — Warm: Session summaries (background Haiku). Load 5 most recent. Build Day 5–6.Layer 3 — Cold: Living user profile (role, goals, key people, patterns, decisions, brick engagement patterns and growth signals). Updated after every session via background Sonnet. Cap 2,000 tokens. Build Day 3–4.Layer 4 — Deep: pgvector embeddings of all summaries. Semantic retrieval when user references past. Build Week 2, activate Week 3.User Profile Structure (Layer 3 profile_json)```typescriptinterface UserProfileJson {  role: string;  industry: string;  businessStage: string;  teamSize: string;  keyPeople: Record<string, string>;       // name > relationship  activeGoals: string[];  decisionPatterns: string[];              // e.g. 'delays when multiple stakeholders'  brickPatterns: Record<number, {          // Accumulated by background Sonnet after each session    sessionCount: number;                  // How many sessions this brick has been active in    lastActive: string;                    // ISO date    growthSignals: Record<string, boolean>; // Latest state of each growth signal flag    trend: 'improving' | 'stable' | 'declining' | 'new';    observations: string | null;           // Most recent summariser observation, max 100 tokens  }>;  cognitiveStyle: string | null;           // Detected over time from conversation patterns (explorer, commander, caretaker, strategist)}```The `brickPatterns` section is updated by background Sonnet after each session using data from `summaryJson.brickGrowthSignals`. This is what enables longitudinal pattern recognition across sessions. When Brick 24 has been active in 4 sessions with `evidence_held: false` each time, the companion can say: "I have noticed something across our conversations. Every time you describe something you have handled well, you find a reason it does not count."Re-entry Prompt with Brick ContinuityWhen a user starts a new session, M5 generates a re-entry prompt. If a brick has been active in 3+ of the last 5 sessions, the re-entry prompt includes the brick pattern summary from profile_json.brickPatterns.Example re-entry context injected into system prompt:> "Last session: discussed hiring decision for site manager role. Brick 24 (Self-Belief) has been active in 4 of your last 5 sessions. Growth signals: instinct_trusted improving, tribe_building not yet started. Trend: improving. Observation: User consistently forms the right judgement then seeks permission to trust it."This gives Sonnet longitudinal awareness without needing the full session history. The re-entry prompt draws from Layer 3 (profile) not Layer 1 (raw transcripts).Token BudgetsBlock	Budget (no files)	Budget (with files)	Source	Management RuleSystem prompt + 24 brick descriptions + metadata instruction	2,000–2,500	2,000–2,500	Static	FixedDeep overlay (Mode 2)	500–1,000	500–1,000	brick_knowledge	Max 2 active. 3rd drops LRUUser profile (Layer 3)	1,000–2,000	1,000–1,500	Encrypted RDS	Cap 2,000 tokens. Trimmed when files presentSession summaries (Layer 2)	1,000–2,000	500–1,000	Encrypted RDS	5 most recent. Trimmed when files presentCurrent session transcript	Max 8,000	Max 6,000	In-memory	When >limit: summarise earlier, keep last 3 exchanges verbatimFile attachments	0	2,000–4,000	S3 + extraction	Large files pre-summarised via Haiku. Week 2 featureSemantic retrieval (Layer 4)	0–1,000	0–500	pgvector	Only when triggered. Week 3TOTAL	~5K–16K	~7K–16K		Target avg <12,000 input tokens. Cost: $0.05–$0.15/message (no files), $0.06–$0.20/message (with files)---Brick Content FormatEach brick has three content layers stored in brick_knowledge, plus two background-process fields. Kristina's full coaching documents are the source material. They get compressed into these formats for the LLM. The source documents are IP and are retained separately.short_description (~80-100 words, ~100-130 tokens): Lives permanently in the system prompt as part of the 24-brick classifier block. Functions as the classifier. Contains: what the brick is, when to activate it (key trigger phrases and patterns), and the core behavioural stance. Written in imperative voice. No theory. No narrative. Every word must help Sonnet identify when this brick is relevant.deep_overlay (~500-800 tokens, hard cap 1,000): Loaded via Mode 2. Contains only instructions that change the LLM's default behaviour. Strip all theory the LLM already knows. Every token must change behaviour. Required structure:STANCE (2-3 sentences): The emotional and relational posture the companion holdsCONSTRAINTS (3-5 rules): What NOT to do. These override the model's natural tendencies. Most important section.CORE MOVE (2-3 sentences): The single most important intervention techniqueCOGNITIVE ADAPTATIONS (4 conditional blocks): If/then patterns matching conversation style to approach. Do not name the styles. Describe the observable pattern and the response.KEY QUESTIONS (5-8): Select based on conversation context. Not a checklist.LONGITUDINAL (2-3 sentences): What to track across sessions. When to name a pattern. References brick_signals metadata tag.construction_overlay (~150-300 tokens): Appended when industry = construction. Contains industry-specific manifestations, terminology, scenarios, and legislation references that are genuinely different from the general deep overlay. Not a repeat with construction examples. Unique content only.summariser_instructions (~50-100 tokens): Appended to the Haiku summarisation prompt when this brick was active in the session. Tells Haiku what specific signals to extract from the transcript.growth_signals (JSONB): Structured flags that background processes extract and track in user_profiles.brickPatterns. Each signal has an "early" state (default false) and flips to true when the "developed" state is observed. The summariser evaluates which state was observed each session.Brick Compression PrincipleDeep overlays are hard-capped at 1,000 tokens per brick. If Kristina's source material for a brick exceeds this, it must be compressed to fit. The compression principle: strip theory the LLM already knows (e.g. what imposter syndrome is, why feedback matters), keep only behavioural redirections that change the model's default response, constraints that override natural tendencies, conditional cognitive style adaptations, key questions, and longitudinal tracking instructions. The LLM is already a capable coach. The deep overlay makes it a specific kind of coach.M3 Session-End Flow (updated)When a session ends, M3 now performs this sequence:Calls `M4.bricks.getSummariserInstructions(activeBrickIds)` to get brick-specific extraction guidance and growth signal definitionsCalls `M5.memory.summariseSession(sessionId, userId, summariserInstructions, growthSignalDefs)` asyncM5 internally: Haiku generates summary with brick-specific instructions appended, then Sonnet updates user profile including brickPatterns---Database SchemaAll encrypted RDS Postgres (AES-256, forced TLS). UUID primary keys. Audit columns on all tables.Table	Key Columns	Notesusers	id, email, stripe_id, tier ('starter'|'pro'), founding_member (boolean), full_access_until (Date), preferred_channel ('email'|'sms'|'both'), phone_number, industry, business_stage, timezone, onboarded_at, cancelled_at, cancel_reason, paused_at, paused_until, referral_code, referred_by, pre_booked_tier	Timezone for Monday/Friday timing. tier drives all feature gating. founding_member = locked-in pricing. full_access_until = 21 days from onboarded_at for Starter (full Pro features during taste period)user_profiles	user_id, profile_text, profile_json, active_bricks[], baseline_scores, version	Layer 3. Cap 2,000 tokens. Versioned (last 5). HIGHEST PII. profile_json includes brick_patterns (see User Profile Structure below)sessions	id, user_id, messages (JSONB), bricks_activated[], started_at, ended_at, message_count, total_input_tokens, total_cost	Layer 1session_events	id, session_id, user_id, message_index, bricks_detected[], confidence, topic_shift, decision_flag, emotional_tone, brick_signals (JSONB), mode2_triggered, mode2_brick_id, ttft_ms, input_tokens, output_tokens, cost, timestamp	Analytics backbone. brick_signals stores longitudinal tracking signals emitted by active deep overlayssession_summaries	session_id, user_id, summary_text, summary_json (JSONB), embedding (vector)	Layers 2+4. summary_json contains: topicsDiscussed, bricksActivated, decisionsReferenced, emotionalArc, brickGrowthSignals, brickObservationsdecisions	id, user_id, session_id, decision_text, options, choice, confidence, reasoning, status, follow_up_date, followed_up_at	Auto-captured via decision flagnudges	id, user_id, trigger_type, nudge_variant ('standard'|'taste_type1'|'taste_type2'|'taste_type3'), content, channel ('email'|'sms'), sent_at, opened_at, clicked_upgrade_at, led_to_session_id	led_to_session_id links nudge to session. nudge_variant tracks taste nudge types for conversion analysis. clicked_upgrade_at tracks taste→upgrade funnelbrick_knowledge	brick_id, pillar, name, short_description, example_phrases[], deep_overlay, construction_overlay, transition_phrases[], brick_metadata_tags[], growth_signals (JSONB), summariser_instructions	short_description in system prompt. deep_overlay loaded on Mode 2. brick_metadata_tags defines what longitudinal signals this brick can emit. growth_signals defines structured flags for background extraction. summariser_instructions appended to Haiku summarisation prompt when this brick was activeartefacts	id, user_id, type, s3_key, period, generated_at	Quarterly reviews. Encrypted S3attachments	id, session_id, user_id, filename, mime_type, s3_key, extracted_text, token_count, summarised, uploaded_at	User file uploads. Encrypted S3. Text extraction cached to avoid reprocessing. Week 2 featureonboarding_funnel	id, user_id, step, timestamp, metadata	Track every funnel step---The 24 Knowledge BricksFive pillars, each containing 3–6 bricks. Decision Mastery (#20) is ALWAYS active.CASH PillarCash Flow Mastery — 13-week forecast, cash conversion cycle, collections rhythm, runway scenarios (WEEK 1)Revenue Growth Engine — Offer positioning, ICP, pipeline stages, sales playbook (WEEK 1)Pricing Power — Pricing strategy, margin visibility, variation management, price increases (WEEK 1)Profit Optimisation — Cost map, top 10 levers, supplier renegotiation, waste removal (WEEK 2)Growth Funding & Leverage — Capital planning, funding options, leverage strategy (WEEK 2)EXECUTION PillarExecution Rhythm — Weekly top 3, meeting rhythm, commitment tracking, critical number (WEEK 1)Systems & Efficiency — Core process identification, documentation, automation (WEEK 2)Tech & AI Advantage — Tool stack simplification, AI use cases, digital presence (WEEK 2)Business Resilience & Compliance — Continuity planning, contracts, compliance calendar (WEEK 1)PEOPLE PillarHiring Excellence — Hiring priority map, role scorecards, interview questions, 30/60/90 onboarding (WEEK 1)Team Development — Skills growth, delegation ladder, coaching rhythm, succession (WEEK 2)Confident Conversations — Conversation prep brief, opening scripts, conflict resolution (WEEK 1)Winning Team Culture — Culture behaviours, recognition rhythms, psychological safety (WEEK 1)Partnership & Co-founder Alignment — Role clarity, decision rights, equity alignment (WEEK 2)STRATEGY PillarProduct/Service Excellence — Product one-pager, value proposition, 3 brand promises (WEEK 2)Customer Excellence — Feedback loops, customer journey map, referral ask script (WEEK 2)Strategic Clarity & Vision — One-page plan, quarterly priorities, stop-doing list (WEEK 1)Channels & Partnerships — Channel strategy, partner pitch, 90-day visibility plan (WEEK 3)Scale & Exit Readiness — Scale readiness, value drivers, founder-dependency reduction (WEEK 3)LEAD MYSELF PillarDecision Mastery — ALWAYS ON. Decision frameworks, composure, confidence, decision journalEnergy & Resilience — Energy rhythm, recovery menu, boundary plan, burnout signals (WEEK 1)Self-Awareness & Growth — How I lead snapshot, feedback plan, 90-day growth plan (WEEK 2)Relationships & Trust — Key relationships, trust building, peer network, tribe building (WEEK 2)Self-Belief & the Imposter — Imposter experience at transitions, evidence-based self-belief, worthiness vs capability, cognitive style adaptations (WEEK 2)---Agent Layer TriggersTrigger	Condition	Action	BuildDecision follow-up	follow_up_date = today/overdue	Nudge referencing specific decision + original confidence	Week 2Monday focus	Every Monday 7am user local time	1 paragraph: last week's commitments + this week's focus	Week 2Friday reflection	Every Friday 4pm user local time	'How did the week go against what you set out to do?'	Week 2Re-engagement	No session in 5+ days	Contextual check-in referencing last session. NEVER generic.	Day 5–6Action not taken	Committed action 2+ sessions ago, not followed up	'You mentioned doing X. Still on your radar?'	Week 2Quarterly review	End of quarter + 4+ sessions	1-page: decisions navigated, patterns, forward look (Pro only)	Week 3+Taste nudge (Starter)	Starter user past full_access_until + decision exists + last taste nudge >14 days ago	Rotate: Type 1 (decision follow-up with value), Type 2 (pattern tease), Type 3 (quarterly preview). Always lead with value. Max 1 per 14 days	Week 2---Safety Guardrails (Built into system prompt Day 1)Scenario	Response	Don'tGenuine distress	Acknowledge weight. Suggest Lifeline (13 11 14), Beyond Blue (1300 22 4636). Stay in conversation.	Don't say 'I'm just an AI.' Don't redirect abruptly.Legal advice	General framing + 'You need a construction lawyer. Want me to help prepare the questions?'	Don't give specific legal advice.Financial advice	Decision framework (options, trade-offs). 'Run it past your accountant.'	Don't recommend specific products.Illegal activity	State risk factually: 'If ATO discovers, penalties include X.'	Don't become complicit. Don't lecture.---Build OrderPhase 1: Foundation (Day 1–2)M8 Event Logger → M1 Auth & Billing → M2 Conversation EnginePhase 2: Intelligence (Day 2–4)M4 Brick Engine → M5 Memory Manager (Layers 1+3) → M3 Context AssemblerPhase 3: Agent + Polish (Day 5–7)M5 Layer 2 (summaries) → M7 Agent Scheduler (basic) → Deploy + E2E testPhase 4: Week 2M9 Voice → M6 Decision Tracker → M7 Full Agent → M5 Layer 4 (semantic) → File Attachments (M3 processing pipeline, S3 storage, frontend drop zone)Each module gets a green checkmark before the next phase starts. If M2 doesn't stream correctly, don't start M3.---Security RequirementsHTTPS everywhere. No exceptions. All endpoints, all internal service communication, all external API calls, all webhooks. No HTTP.All data encrypted at rest (AES-256) and in transit (TLS 1.2+)No public database endpointsNo PII in logsUser data never used for model training (confirmed via API terms)Full account deletion pipelineAustralian Privacy Act compliance at launchGDPR-ready architectureSOC 2 controls built in from day oneUser profile (Layer 3) treated as medical records — highest PII sensitivityHSTS headers on all responsesAll cookies: Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite=Strict---Pricing Architecture (CONFIRMED)All prices in AUD.Tiers	Starter	Pro	EnterprisePrice	$29 AUD/month	$59 AUD/month	Contact usFounding member price	$29 (locked for life)	$49 for first year	CustomStripe ConfigurationThree Price objects on one Product:`price_starter` = $29 AUD/month`price_pro` = $59 AUD/month`price_pro_founding` = $49 AUD/month (first year, then transitions to $59)Enterprise: custom invoicing, not self-serveFeature Gating by TierFeature	Starter $29	Pro $59Text conversation	✓ Always	✓ Always24 bricks + construction overlays	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysMode 2 deep overlays	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysDecision Mastery (always-on)	✓ Always	✓ Always4-layer memory	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysMonday 7am focus (email or SMS)	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysFriday 4pm reflection (email or SMS)	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysDelivery choice (email/SMS/both)	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysRe-engagement nudges	✓ Always	✓ AlwaysDecision journal + follow-ups	✓ First 3 weeks only	✓ AlwaysAction tracking + commitment nudges	✓ First 3 weeks only	✓ AlwaysPeriodic taste nudges (after week 3)	✓ See below	Not neededVoice input	✗	✓File uploads	✗	✓Pattern recognition	✗	✓Quarterly leadership reviews	✗	✓Tier Logic in M7 Agent Scheduler```If nudge_type is 'decision_followup' or 'action_tracking':  If user.tier === 'pro': generate and send normally  If user.tier === 'starter' AND today < user.full_access_until: generate and send normally  If user.tier === 'starter' AND today >= user.full_access_until:    check if taste_nudge is due (max 1 per 14 days)    if yes: generate taste nudge variant    if no: skip```Taste Nudge System (Starter Users After Week 3)Three types, rotated, max one per fortnight:Type 1 — Decision follow-up with value: Gives the actual follow-up AND mentions Pro tracks this automatically. Always lead with value.Type 2 — Pattern tease (after 2+ months): Mentions a pattern has been spotted but doesn't reveal it. The hook.Type 3 — Quarterly review preview (after 3+ months): Shows the data exists. Review itself behind upgrade.Rules: Always give value in the nudge. Never just tease. Reference specific decisions. Tone = Companion genuinely helping, not a paywall. Kristina writes all taste nudge copy.Upgrade FlowStripe upgrades subscription. Pro-rated for current period`tier` field updates immediately. All feature gates openWithin 1 hour: M7 picks up all open decisions/actions and sends "welcome to Pro" nudge with immediate follow-up on oldest open itemDowngrade FlowCapture reason (mandatory)Offer one month Pro free before downgradingIf proceed: decision follow-ups stop after current billing period. Monday/Friday continue. Decision journal data preservedPre-Launch Landing PageThree CTAs:Join Waitlist — free, email captureLock in Founding Starter — $29/month, card taken, charged at launchPre-book Founding Pro — $49/month (normally $59), card taken, charged at launchPre-book data tracked in `pre_booked_tier` field and onboarding_funnel events.SMS DeliveryBoth tiers get email, SMS, or both for all nudges. User chooses during onboarding. Delivered via Twilio or Amazon SNS. Cost: ~$0.05–$0.08 AUD per SMS. Week 2 build.Cost TargetsTarget avg <12,000 input tokens per interactionPrompt caching active on static system prompt (~2,500 tokens at 90% discount)Smart model routing: ~40% of messages to Haiku (acknowledgements, simple follow-ups)Cost per session: <$0.15 avgLLM cost/user/month: <$5.00 AUD (Starter), <$10.00 AUD (Pro avg)Time to first token: <2,000ms p95Mode 2 follow-up latency: <3,000msError rate: <1%SMS cost/user/month: ~$0.50 AUD (if SMS enabled)Revenue MilestonesMonth	Users	Starter %	Pro %	MRR (AUD)	Blended ARPU1	30	93%	7%	$930	$313	150	88%	12%	$4,890	$336	500	80%	20%	$17,500	$3512	2,500	70%	30%	$94,500	$3818	5,000	60%	40%	$205,000	$41